It requires a high degree of organisational, technical and financial effort.
The construction and development of a sustainable European transport infrastructure often requires difficult compromises with European and national policy objectives, such as environmental conservation.
It is precisely because of the necessary environmental protection measures that the construction of the transport infrastructure is costly.
When planning and awarding the construction of transport routes, administrations can, through careful action and decision-making, save significant financial resources and use them for other useful purposes.
One of the tasks of state auditing authorities is to identify deficiencies that hinder optimal economy, efficiency and effectiveness in spending on construction of transport facilities.
Audit authorities should not only draw the attention of administrations to the shortcomings identified, but also propose improvements for the benefit of citizens and Europe.
Summary
In 2005 and 2006, the two Supreme Audit Institutions of the Federal Republic of Germany and the Czech Republic, the Federal Court of Auditors (BRH) and the Nejvy's (NK'), conducted parallel audits of the expenditure for the construction of the Prague-Dresden motorway (Motorway D 8 in the Czech Republic and A 17 in Germany).
The two highways are connected by a border bridge jointly funded by both states.
The cooperation with the NKx enabled the BRH to carry out an in-depth assessment of the efficiency of the intermediate operation in the construction of the border bridge.
As part of the collaboration with the BRH, the NKx received data from German bridges and tunnels for its own cost comparisons.
In 2000, the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany concluded a contract for the construction of the border bridge.
In line with planning progress, the completion date was finally set at the end of 2006.
However, during the award process, the Czech Republic's Roads and Motorways Directorate (RMD) made errors that delayed the procedure and reduced the available construction time.
The contract with the contractor was therefore concluded later than planned.
The contractor secured the accelerated construction of the bridge by the end of 2006.
For this, however, the RMD had to incur significant additional costs.
As part of the joint audit activity, the prices of motorway bridges at D8 and A17 were compared.
A price analysis on hand statistical methods identified bridges with high costs per square meter.
The analysis found that the Borders Bridge was the most expensive among large bridges with lengths of over 100m.
This was also due to the price increase as a result of procurement delays.
Comparison of the prices of tunnels showed that the D8 prices of tunnels are significantly higher than those of similar tunnels in Germany.
In future assessments of the efficiency of transport infrastructure spending, both BRH and NK' will be able to rely on a data collection of bridge and tunnel prices.
Both billing yards recommend standardizing bridge designs and executing steel composite and special constructions only where tension concrete constructions are inappropriate.
The course of exams was characterised by teamwork and an open approach.
During the parallel exam, the examiners of both sides exchanged their expertise and skill.
Introduction
This report concerns parallel audits of the construction of the motorway from Dresden to Prague (D 8 in the Czech Republic and A 17 in Germany).
Audit priorities included thrift, cost-effectiveness and effectiveness of use of funds.
The parallel tests were conducted by BRH in Germany and NK' in the Czech Republic
in 2005 and 2006 by .
It examined austerity, efficiency and effectiveness of the D8 motorway's cross-border section 0807 expenditure of around CZK 20 billion gross (approx. 690 million).
Of this amount, 64 million will be made available from the EU Structural Funds (ISPA).
The BRH had already examined the design and construction of the A17 motorway in 2003-2005, independently of the parallel tests with the NKx.
Of the financial volume for the construction of all three A17 sections of about 670 million, 277 million will be co-financed by the European Fund (ERDF).
The Prague-Dresden motorway is part of the Pan-European Transport Corridor IV Dresden - Central and South Eastern Europe - Istanbul.
The D8 runs from Prague through Usti nad Labem to the Czech/German border,
the A17 from the border to Dresden.
At the time of the audit, the border sections of the highways were under construction.
Both sections were opened to traffic on 21 December 2006.
While the motorway is thus completed on the German side to Dresden, the D 8 on the Czech side remains incomplete as the 0805 section between Rehlovice and Lovosice is still in the planning phase.
There is provision for the crossing of a landscape reserve in the Bohemian Central Mountains.
According to Czech forecasts from 2001, the volume of traffic in 2008 will be 22,940 cars per day in section 0807.
German forecasts estimate traffic on the A17 at the Czech border at around 25 000 cars per day in 2010.
In 2000, the Federal Republic of Germany and the Czech Republic concluded a contract to merge the German A 17 motorway and the Czech D8 motorway at the common state border by building a border bridge.
Since both states are involved in the construction of this bridge, this single construction measure was an important aspect of the parallel audits of both courts of auditors.
Collaboration between Brh and Nkx
From mid-2005, the two courts of auditors jointly considered cooperation in examining the construction of the Prague-Dresden motorway.
Both sides had important reasons for this cooperation:
1.
Germany is partly funding the construction of the border bridge.
Planning and construction are the responsibility of the Czech road construction administration.
There was no possibility for the BRH to examine this construction project itself.
2.
It did not have comparative data to assess whether the funds were used sparingly with respect to the overall construction costs of the bridges and tunnels at the D8.
3.
It also needed to examine the effectiveness of spending by examining the key technical parameters of bridges and tunnels to ensure equal quality of use on both sides of the border.
Following preparatory negotiations, the presidents of the two courts of auditors concluded an agreement on the coordination of tests of the Prague-Dresden motorway on 4 January 2006.
The auditors of both courts of auditors met at about six- to eight-week intervals during 2006.
In doing so, they addressed current problems and tasks, devised a uniform methodology for examining bridge and tunnel prices, exchanged audit results on building the border bridge, and produced joint reports.
The ongoing exchange of information was essential to the cooperation.
While the BRH focused on comparing the technical parameters of bridges and tunnels, as well as procurement procedures, it mostly developed the methodology for analyzing bridge and tunnel prices.
In Germany and the Czech Republic, the legal basis for financial control differs and so does the way the two audit bodies complete their audits.
The two authorities therefore each produced separate national reports on their audit results.
This report takes into account the results of the two parallel audits.
The cooperation will end with the signing of a final communiqué in the first half of 2007.
Construction of the Borders Bridge
In the 2000 Treaty, the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany agreed to complete the border bridge if possible in 2005.
It later moved the date by consensus to the end of 2006.
The RMD acted as the contractor of the construction measure.
Germany co-finances the construction of bridges.
Initially, the RMD envisaged a tension concrete construction for the border bridge.
However, the RMD agreed with its German partner in 1999 to build a steel composite construction.
They based this decision on the possible reduction of the number of pillar pairs from seven to five and the associated environmental benefits for the Talaue.
In addition, a comparative calculation of the RMD had designated steel composite construction as the more cost-effective solution.
This, however, was due to a calculation error.
The calculation assumed a length of the new steel composite construction of only 397 m,
In fact, however, it is 5 per cent longer.
During the procurement process,
