These errors led to subjective and ambiguous assessments by the Appraisal Commission and the Director General of RMD.
An underperforming bidder challenged the outcome of the procurement process.
The subsequent investigation by the Czech Cartel Office delayed the signing of the construction contract for the border bridge.
As a result, the summer construction season following the bid review was lost in 2004 and the total construction time available was shortened.
The contractor agreed to build the bridge in a shorter time, leading to a substantial price increase.
Measures offered included double fitting of the superstructures, changing the pillar shape and erecting an assembly hall.
In addition, the contractor was unable to procure the steel variety originally envisaged.
The new steel variety, with a higher cost of around 4 million, enabled to reduce the construction time for corrosion protection and thus the total construction time.
Compared to the offer price of approx. 18.3 million net, the acceleration measures and further additions will substantially increase the total construction costs of the border bridge.
The shortened construction period alone led to a price increase of about 5.9 million euros.
The cost, excluding price guiding, is currently around 25.9 million net (as of October 2006).
Comparison of the prices of bridges and tunnels
Both auditors examined bridge prices at the D 8 and A 17 to identify bridges characterised by particularly high prices and compare bridge prices on the German and Czech sides.
The research was based on mathematical statistical methods.
The tunnels on the D 8 were compared with similar tunnels on the German A71, A38 and A4 motorways, as comparable tunnels on the A 17 did not exist.
In preparing this part of the review, a precise definition of the price concept was important.
For comparison of bridge prices both courts agreed detailed targets, such as: to use the current price paid for the bridge without VAT.
(VAT rates in the Czech Republic and Germany are different and may change) not to take into account the cost of specific start-up measures, to use the European Central Bank rate of 30.12.2005 for currency conversion (29 CZK x 1 per cent).
Bridges of various types of construction (steel concrete, span concrete, steel composite and steel) and various sizes are present at both the D 8 and the A 17.
To ensure comparability of the tested bridge buildings, the bridges were grouped by their design.
The analyses also took into account bridge size within these groups.
By far the most common on both sides of the border were concrete bridges (20 bridges on the D 8 and 36 bridges on the A 17).
The research focused on this type of bridge as the size of the sample allowed the use of mathematical statistical methods and improved the reliability of the results.
The research showed the M2 price of concrete bridges on the D 8/A 17 depends on bridge size (length, road surface): the larger the bridge, the lower the square metre price.
For German bridges, the correlation between price and size is more pronounced than for Czech bridges (see illustrations below).
At the A 17, two, at the D 8, four bridges could be detected with a significantly increased price.
These bridges were partly determined by a method for identifying significant deviations within a sample and partly by regression analysis of the correlation between bridge price and size (based on the distance to the regression curve, atypically expensive bridges can be identified).
But the atypically high price of these bridges should serve only as a guide to which bridges to focus on.
In order to draw definitive conclusions, the causes of the high price must be identified on a case-by-case basis.
This could be due to inefficient administration, environmental protection or other legitimate reasons.
Taking into account the greater average length of Czech concrete bridges compared to German ones (see chart 1), the proven negative correlation between bridge price and length led Czech concrete bridges to expect to be cheaper.
This was in addition to the lower labour costs in the Czech Republic compared with Germany.
However, the evaluation of the results showed that the price of concrete bridges at the D 8 is higher than the A 17.
Two reasons for this were identified at joint meetings:
1.
In Germany, construction contracts for bridges are mainly awarded separately.
This also allows SMEs to participate in the award competition.
In the Czech Republic, many bridge buildings are awarded as part of larger contracts to build several kilometres of motorway sections.
Orders of this magnitude cannot be handled by medium-sized companies.
2.
In the Czech Republic, the variety of built bridge structures is greater than in Germany.
