Economics and effectiveness of the Dresden - Prague motorway
The independent Czech Republic was founded in 1993.
That same year, the government passed the plan for expanding the highway network.
It provided for the gradual expansion of the D8 from Prague to the state border with Germany.
The section 0805 was to be built by the central Bohemian Mountains in front of the border section 0807.
The Czech Republic finances the D8 within the framework of programme financing.
The programme number 327 220 "Construction of the motorway D 8 Prague - "st" nad Labem - Czech German border" defines two objectives:
1.
as a national objective: to improve the connection between Prague and Oesti nad Labem;
2.
as an international objective: the link between Prague and Berlin as part of the Pan-European Transport Corridor IV BerlinIstanbul.
The programme provided for the construction of the section leading through the Bohemian Central Mountains to be completed in June 2008 and the construction of the border section 0807 in June 2007.
It should be noted that the end of construction is not identical to the time of commissioning.
It noted that the planning decision had already been adopted for the construction of the section leading through the Bohemian Central Mountains.
Environmental groups have sued against that decision.
A final ruling is pending.
Therefore, a delay of several years in completing section No.0805 could not be ruled out compared to the schedule provided for in the programme documentation.
In the summer of 2006, the Czech Ministry of Transport proposed that the completion date of Section No.0805 be postponed until 2010.
As a result, the construction of the border section did not achieve the national objective of improving the connection between Prague and Usti nad Labem.
The RMD examined the borderline section 0807 of the D8 and section 0805 of the Bohemian Mountains between 1999 and 2001.
As a cost of the investment, the Commission set aside some 639 million euros for both sections 0805 and 0807.
