The 2001 performance survey was based on the assumption that the section bordering and leading through the Bohemian mid-mountain simultaneously went under traffic.
At the time of the audit it was obvious that the section through the Bohemian Central Mountains will not be opened at the original date.
This reduces the above EIRR values.
The cost of both sections at 31/12/2005 was 897 million euro excluding VAT, 27.4 percent higher than in 2001 as a result.
There is also a risk that Section 0805 will get another more elaborate in-line, which would affect the economics of the project.
The cost-effectiveness assessment showed that the construction of both sections of the motorway is economically justified with daily traffic of at least 18,000 cars per day in 2010.
However, a study on diversion routes as an alternative to the missing section through the central Bohemian mountains assumes traffic volumes of 12 600 to 13 750 cars per day in 2007.
Increased traffic on the routes intended to replace the missing section with the Bohemian Central Mountains is highly likely to result in congestion and thus increased external costs that were not taken into account in the original cost-effectiveness study.
The aforementioned reduction in revenue and increase in costs means that the already low EIRR for the construction of the borderline section of the D 8 will not be achieved.
The construction of the border section of the D8 is therefore uneconomical.
The construction of the A17 also experienced cost increases, as in the construction of the two sections of the D8.
In the context of the macroeconomic assessment for the 1992 Federal Road Plan, the Federal Ministry for Transport estimated an investment cost of around 320 million euros.
In doing so, it identified a benefit/cost ratio of 4.6.
Costs have now increased to around 670 million and benefit/cost ratios have been reduced by more than half.
The BRH had independently assessed the efficiency of the design and construction of the A17 motorway between 2003 and 2005.
In doing so, he noted that the authority responsible for the permit called for a non-essential landscape tunnel for the third section of the A 17.
The BRH managed to convince the Federal Ministry and the Roads Administration of the abundance of the landscape tunnel during the course of the audit.
This enabled the avoidance of 10 million in construction costs and 150,000 in annual operating costs.
When examining the first section of the A17, the BRH found that the construction was inadequately prepared.
The following example illustrates this:
The Roads Administration waived a condition recording of the rock on the surface of the Dölzschen wall at the planning stage, as it was difficult to access.
It was only when the tunnel advance reached the wall that she picked this up.
This showed that the rock was more weathered than assumed when tendered.
Elaborate measures such as anchorages, injections and rock impact protection nets for around 3.3 million were necessary.
The Roads Administration not only bore the cost of additional, already required services such as securing the Dölzschen wall, but also those that would not have been required at all if construction had been properly prepared.
These include expenditure due to disrupted construction (3.2 million), additional installation of the Advance Team (0.5 million) and increased wages and material prices due to the extension of construction time (7 million).
There is no lasting added value to this additional expenditure of around 10.7 million.
The BRH took this and other measures as an opportunity to ask the Federal Ministry to better exercise the specialist supervision of major road construction.
In this context, it should insist that road administrations introduce quality assurance systems.
Benefits of cooperation for BRH and NK. The cooperation met the expectations of both courts of auditors.
The BRH received findings on the planning, procurement and implementation of the construction of the border bridge.
Both courts of auditors developed a data backlog on bridge and tunnel prices that will be helpful in future audits.
It found that the main engineering parameters for the bridges, tunnels and roadways of the D 8 are no different from those of the A 17.
The auditors of both courts involved in the collaboration gathered valuable experience that will be useful in future audits.
